data.title: Person: Paul Stephenson
data.meta_description: Person: Paul Stephenson: A comprehensive series of articles on this topic
data.text:
property

Ring of Kerry village holiday homes scheme sale at €4.1m

A development of 24 holiday homes, bought four years ago at auction as an uncompleted development which had started construction in 2007, is now for sale, trading all-year around, earning €272,000 per year in income, and scoring an impressive 9.8 out of 10 user satisfaction rating on booking.com.

Private investors are being invited to become ‘King of the Castle,’ as a Tralee town centre bank, occupied by Bank of Ireland on Castle Street, is being touted for sale, with an attractive rental income of €277,000 pa.

Scotland Yard has urged Portuguese authorities to re-open the search for Madeleine McCann as detectives said there were 195 potential leads to finding her alive.

Rebekah Brooks is believed to be among 11 suspects in the phone-hacking scandal facing criminal charges after police sent their first set of files to prosecutors.

Three Scotland Yard officers involved in the original police investigation into phone hacking at the News of the World (NotW) will give evidence to the Leveson Inquiry today.

Five people have been arrested over payments to police officers in the phone-hacking inquiry, Scotland Yard said.

The final total of people whose phones were hacked by the News of the World will be about 800, it was reported today.

FOUR applicants are set to fight it out to be London’s new police chief and take on responsibility for running Britain’s biggest police force as it battles with the aftermath of serious rioting and a high-profile investigation which has put some of its own staff under the spotlight.

A former News of the World executive arrested in relation to phone hacking was being questioned by detectives in custody today.

Rupert Murdoch has said he will do “whatever is necessary” to prevent the phone hacking scandal occurring again, as his News Corporation conglomerate reported a rise in annual profits to $2.74bn.

BRITISH Prime Minister David Cameron came under renewed pressure over the phone-hacking scandal, as he told MPs he was “extremely sorry” for the furore caused by his appointment of Andy Coulson as Downing Street communications chief.

BRITISH Prime Minister David Cameron was last night flying back to London to address the crisis over phone hacking and police links with the media, cutting short a two-day visit to Africa.

Rupert Murdoch and his son James will appear before MPs today to face their intensely-awaited grilling on the News of the World phone-hacking scandal.

FATHER-and-son act Rupert and James Murdoch top the bill today in what promises to be a day of gripping political drama in the normally staid surroundings of the parliament’s committee rooms.

THE whistleblower News of the World reporter who alleged Andy Coulson “encouraged” him to hack phones has been found dead.

John Yates announced his resignation as one of Britain’s top police officers today after coming under mounting pressure over his handling of the phone hacking scandal.

THE FBI has opened an investigation into allegations that media mogul Rupert Murdoch’s News Corporation sought to hack into the phones of 9/11 victims, according to a law enforcement official.
